4. Data Processing#

To simplify and automate future data collection efforts, a framework was developed to automate the process of logging in, downloading, and processing data via the CDRC UI as well as obtaining metadata. This avoids the need to manually download and work with files and can be expanded in the future by creating a scraper to extract a list of all available datasets and their metadata to enable a more programmatic approach to data discovery.

4.1. Data Collection & Processing#

The OAC dataset was downloaded in GeoPackage format as it is more modern, less restrictive, and available as a single file and avoids issues inherent to the multi-file Shapefile format, such as column length limits and other well-known drawbacks [Cepicky and s.r.o., 2017].

Following this, the data was manipulated using DuckDB, a lightweight, in-process SQL database management system (DBMS). DuckDB, along with its spatial extension, is well suited to the task of manipulating and analysing in-memory geospatial data. Further, while a relatively new tool it is quickly gaining traction in the geospatial community and allows data processing to occur via SQL queries, which allows for transparent, reproducible, and portable code that could be replicated elsewhere (modified to work on BigQuery, PostGIS, MSSQL) in the future.

Finally, the data was written and stored into a compressed Parquet file, which is a columnar storage format that is well suited to the storage of tabular data. This format was chosen due to being an open format, reduced file size (as it is to be stored in GitHub), and as it can be efficiently processed using a variety of tools. In addition, there is ongoing work on GeoParquet, which is a spatial extension to the Parquet format that is progressing rapidly with major backing from Microsoft and Databricks.

Show code cell source Hide code cell source 
import duckdb
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd

con = duckdb.connect(database=":memory:")
con.install_extension("spatial")
con.load_extension("spatial")

metadata = pd.read_parquet("../data/cdrc/oac_2021_metadata.parquet")
lookup = pd.read_parquet("../data/cdrc/oac_2021_lookup.parquet")
data_file = "../data/cdrc/oac_2021.parquet.gzip"
query = f"""
SELECT
    oa_code_21
    , la_code_23
    , super_grp
    , grp
    , sub_grp
    , ST_ASHEXWKB(ST_GeomFromWKB(geom_wkb_4326)) AS geom_hexwkb_4326
FROM READ_PARQUET("{data_file}")
WHERE la_code_23 = 'E08000021'
;
"""

df = con.sql(query).df()
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(
    df.drop(columns=["geom_hexwkb_4326"]),
    geometry=gpd.GeoSeries.from_wkb(df["geom_hexwkb_4326"]),
    crs="EPSG:4326",
)

As the dataset is liable to change over time, it was essential to store the metadata to enable understanding of the dataset at the time of collection. Further, the OAC dataset is accompanied by a PDF file that includes information about each Supergroup, Group, and Subgroup, crucially including the characteristics and demographics of each. The dataset itself only includes short codes which is not particularly useful in isolation. The PDF file was therefore parsed to extract the information and stored in a parquet lookup file that can be used to join to the OAC dataset or simply as an information lookup in its own right. Ideally, this information would be provided in a machine-readable format, however, this may be pending given the relative newness of the dataset.
